-- в”Ђв”Ђ Trivy в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Trivy is Aqua Security's free, open-source all-in-one scanner that finds vulnerabilities, misconfigurations, secrets, and license issues across containers, code repositories, and cloud infrastructure.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$open-source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2019, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$501-1,000 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Boston, Massachusetts, United States (dual headquarters in Ramat Gan, Israel)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Trivy Review: Aqua Security's Free Vulnerability Scanner$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Trivy is a free, open-source scanner for container, code, and cloud vulnerabilities, misconfigurations, and secrets. See features, pricing, and comparisons.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Trivy is a free, open-source security scanner originally created as an independent project by developer Teppei Fukuda in 2019, and adopted by Aqua Security shortly after, becoming the company's flagship open-source tool. Aqua Security itself was founded in 2015 (originally as Scalock) and is headquartered in Boston, Massachusetts and Ramat Gan, Israel. Trivy scans five target types, including container images, filesystems, git repositories, virtual machine images, and Kubernetes clusters, using four scanning engines that detect vulnerabilities, misconfigurations, exposed secrets, and license compliance issues in a single unified tool. It ships as a single self-contained binary with no external dependencies such as a database or middleware, so it can be downloaded and run immediately, which has made it popular in CI/CD pipelines. Trivy pulls vulnerability data from the Aqua Vulnerability Database and other public sources, and is known for low false-positive rates on historically noisy operating systems like Alpine Linux and RHEL/CentOS. It is released under the Apache 2.0 license and remains fully free with no feature gating between community and commercial use; Aqua Security instead monetizes through the separate, commercial Aqua Platform (a full CNAPP offering runtime protection, centralized dashboards, and compliance tooling) that is built on top of Trivy's scanning engine. With more than 36,000 GitHub stars and over 500 contributors, Trivy is widely cited as the most-starred open-source security scanner on GitHub and is commonly compared to alternatives such as Grype, Snyk Open Source, and Clair. It is a standard choice for DevSecOps teams that want vulnerability, secret, and misconfiguration scanning built directly into CI/CD without paying for a commercial license.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '2d2c7247-cad0-4d55-bf16-9fd4c2b6499d';

