-- в”Ђв”Ђ Tryton в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Tryton is a free, open-source, three-tier ERP framework built in Python that covers accounting, sales, inventory, CRM, and supply chain management for organizations that want full control of their business software.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$open-source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2008, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Belgium$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Dutch$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Tryton Review: Free Open-Source ERP Framework$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Tryton is a free, GPL-licensed ERP framework in Python covering accounting, sales, CRM, and inventory. See features, governance, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Tryton is a free, open-source enterprise resource planning (ERP) framework written in Python with a PostgreSQL database backend. It began as a fork of version 4.2 of TinyERP, the project that later became OpenERP and is now known as Odoo, created by developers Cedric Krier and Bertrand Chenal in response to disagreements over the original project's technical direction and licensing. Tryton's first release shipped in November 2008. Rather than building a traditional partner-reseller network like most commercial ERP vendors, Tryton adopted a federation governance model similar to PostgreSQL, where multiple independent companies across countries including France, Spain, Colombia, and Germany jointly contribute to and support the project. Since December 2012, the project has been formally stewarded by the Tryton Foundation, a Belgian non-profit organization that owns the trademark and coordinates infrastructure and community activities. The platform and its official modules are licensed under GPL-3.0-or-later, making them entirely free to use, modify, and redistribute. Tryton follows a three-tier architecture with a client (traditionally GTK-based, alongside a web client), an application server, and a PostgreSQL database, and it ships with modules covering double-entry accounting, sales and purchasing, inventory and warehouse management, CRM, project management, and manufacturing. The project follows a six-month release cycle with a one-year maintenance window per release, with the 7.0 series being the stable line as of mid-2025, and the software is available in more than 25 languages. Because it is entirely open source with no official managed cloud product, Tryton is best compared to Odoo (its commercially-oriented cousin) and ERPNext, appealing most to organizations and developers who want a vendor-neutral, self-hosted ERP without subscription fees or a mandatory partner relationship.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'fac895ab-84a4-44ef-95ce-d865e6760f3c';

